The world born of September 11.
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th commemoration of the September 11 terrorist attacks in the United States.
That day, 19 terrorists had taken control of four commercial planes, launched two of the aircraft at the World Trade Center towers in New York, struck the Pentagon with a third, and then led to the crash of a fourth plane in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another American government building in Washington, DC.
All the hijackers were from the Middle East, and 15 from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of a planned operation, organized and led by Al-Qaeda (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
At the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women, and children were killed, and more than 6,000 were injured.
Most were Americans, although citizens from over a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that September 11 would usher in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other attacks carried out by Al-Qaeda followed, including several explosions on Madrid's trains in March 2004, and the attack carried out on London's public transportation in July 2005.
Terrorists pledging allegiance to the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and orchestrated a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to strike pedestrians).
For all its might, neither the United States nor any of its allies have ever suffered an attack of comparable scope to those of September 11 – which are in a league of their own.
It is thus worth asking: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference did September 11 make ?
Has history changed and, if so, to what extent ?
Many reasons explain why the terrorists were unable to carry out any other major attacks.
After the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaeda lost its sanctuary.
Almost all governments around the world have put in place screening procedures making it harder for potential terrorists to access airports and planes.
Governments have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities in order to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the rare domains where states often in disagreement are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is now a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a level of support for the principle that governments cannot distinguish between terrorists and those who provide them with sanctuary and support.
The days are over when individuals and groups willing to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters.
It is not to claim that terrorism has stopped claiming several tens of thousands of lives every year.
However, most attacks occur in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia as part of ongoing conflicts (primarily in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks, such as those of September 11, against major powers.
Terrorism is increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaeda, for example, survived the elimination of Osama bin Laden by US special forces in Pakistan, nearly a decade after the September 11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no resolution of the issue on the horizon.
The possibility of a new September 11 cannot be ruled out, although the US government has recently stated that the "most urgent terrorist threat" to the country lies domestically.
As formulated by the Provisional Irish Republican Army after their failed attempt to assassinate British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, "Today we haven't been lucky, but remember that it's enough to be lucky once.
You'll always need it.
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists will get their hands on nuclear material, or will be able to manufacture and use a biological or chemical weapon, at which point terrorism could determine the course of history.
For the time being, it is not the case.
September 11 has nonetheless marked a historical turning point, with a profound impact on US foreign policy over the past 20 years.
If the attacks did not lead to a global era of terrorism, they certainly gave rise to the famous global war on terror, with major consequences for US behavior around the world, America's image in the eyes of the world, and the way many Americans came to view their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Peu après les September 11 attacks, the United States offered the Taliban, which controlled the Afghan government at the time, a choice: hand over the Al-Qaeda leaders on the verge of leaving the country and responsible for organizing the September 11 attacks, or risk their rule.
After the Taliban refused to hand over Al-Qaeda leaders, US intelligence and military collaborated with an unstructured Afghan tribal confederation known as the Northern Alliance to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
This control was never total, nor uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaeda sought refuge in neighboring Pakistan, where they gradually regained strength and resumed their military operations against the government that had replaced them.
The United States did not sufficiently work to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of a sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, America reinforced its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, essentially becoming a key partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, the US intervention in Afghanistan mobilized more than 100,000 US soldiers.
Over more than twenty years, the cost of operations has risen to over $2 trillion, resulting in more than 2,300 US lives lost, and tens of thousands of Afghan lives.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The US presence deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy, and fueled opposition to the US, while the Taliban proved more persistent than America, which in 2020 had lost all will to fight in a conflict doomed to end in an indefinite stalemate.
The global war on terror has also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have taken military action if September 11 had not occurred.
The attacks have certainly reinforced his tendency to signal to the world that the United States were not, as President Richard Nixon had formulated during the Vietnam War, a "helpless and pitiful giant".
This led certain members of the administration (notably Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse the risk of seeing terrorists obtain weapons of mass destruction, which Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (although this was ultimately not the case), according to most participants.
Some envisioned spreading democracy in Iraq, then across the entire Middle East, considering that this endeavor was not only achievable, but also would make the region far less likely to produce terrorists and support them.
La war in Iraq, launched in March 2003, did not unfold as the Bush administration and many members of Congress (including then-Senator Joe Biden) and world leaders who had endorsed it had hoped or anticipated.
The United States were not prepared for the essential events to come.
Military victories initially secured in the first phase certainly allowed for the ousting of the government, but quickly gave way to widespread unrest and a violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army, and to exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs, further exacerbated a situation that was already chaotic.
Iraq, like Afghanistan, has fundamentally shown the limits of what military force can achieve at a reasonable cost and within a reasonable timeframe.
In the end, the United States was forced to strengthen its military presence, to nearly 170,000 troops, in order to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability has been achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but at a much heavier human cost: over 4,000 US soldiers killed, a far greater number of wounded, and a skyrocketing rate of suicides among American military personnel (in both Iraq and Afghanistan).
This total excludes, however, deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for whom estimates vary widely, but whose number is certainly in the hundreds of thousands.
The war in Iraq has also weakened the United States in other respects.
No evidence has ever demonstrated Iraq's involvement in the September 11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for a military intervention without UN approval – aimed at eliminating Saddam's weapons of mass destruction – proved to be based on no real grounds.
Images of US soldiers mistreating Iraqi prisoners have further tarnished the country's reputation.
In addition, a war-torn Iraq has become synonymous with an emerging Iran as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if considering Israel).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
While the United States became heavily engaged in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking in major powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted against the United States, both in Europe and East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia, as well as a stronger and more assertive China.
The global war on terror has not provided and has not provided the United States with a compass in their approach to foreign policy in the face of a renewed rivalry between great powers.
The wars waged in the aftermath of September 11 have also had significant domestic consequences for the United States.
They shook the confidence in a country that had emerged from the Cold War with a historically unparalleled preponderant power, and undermined the national unity that had surfaced in the immediate aftermath of the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars have also fueled opposition to a major and lasting global role for the United States, giving rise to a new trend of isolationism.
Similarly, this martial propensity, associated with the 2007-2009 global financial crisis and its economic fallout, has severely impacted the Americans' confidence in the elite, thus stimulating the rise of a populist sentiment that, among other consequences, contributed to the rise of Donald Trump.
America today is more divided than ever domestically, and less inclined to pursue this form of active foreign policy that has characterized it since the end of World War II, and which has largely benefited Americans as well as many others.
In hindsight, we can now consider September 11 as a harbinger of what was to come: not the globalization of terrorism, but the fears of globalization.
The attacks sent a message that distance and borders mattered little in the global era.
Nothing remains local for long anymore, whether it's the terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis that originated in poor American financial management.
We are currently all facing a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its appearance in China in December 2019.
The fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves that devastate many regions around the world are the consequence of climate change, itself a cumulative effect of human activity that releases unsustainable quantities of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era begun by recent events comes full circle, marking the 20th anniversary of the US intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly ousted from power; in recent weeks, they have regained it just as easily.
It is too early to tell if the Taliban will resume their old habits by once again becoming a haven for terrorism, and if terrorists worldwide will boast of their victory over America and its allies.
What we know, on the other hand, is that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that already determines it.
